        <item>
            <title>0.3.628</title>
            <pubDate>Thu, 16 Jul 2026 08:47:31 -0700</pubDate>
            <sparkle:version>628</sparkle:version>
            <sparkle:shortVersionString>0.3.628</sparkle:shortVersionString>
            <sparkle:minimumSystemVersion>14.0</sparkle:minimumSystemVersion>
            <description><![CDATA[<h2>ChainLink 0.3.628</h2>
<p class="sub">Bike Fit can now look up a bike's geometry for you, a coach that can check the web, and polish.</p>

<h3>Bike Fit — look up a bike's geometry</h3>
<ul>
  <li>In <b>Candidate Bikes</b>, type a brand + model and its frame size, click <b>Look up geometry</b>,
  and ChainLink searches the web for the manufacturer's published <b>stack and reach</b> and fills the
  fields — then judges whether your measured position is reachable on that bike.</li>
  <li>It shows where the numbers came from and reminds you to double-check the maker's chart. Once looked
  up, the same bike + size is <b>remembered</b>, so re-checking it is instant.</li>
  <li>New separate <b>Frame size</b> field so you're prompted for it.</li>
</ul>

<h3>A coach that can check the web</h3>
<ul>
  <li>The AI coach can now do a real <b>web search</b> for current facts — a bike's geometry or weight,
  a component spec or price, an event date — instead of answering from memory. It uses whichever coach
  you've set up (<b>Claude, OpenAI, or Google Gemini</b>); no extra key needed.</li>
  <li>On the private on-device coach (which can't reach the web), it now says so clearly.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Fixes &amp; polish</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Bike Fit now catches an <b>impossible saddle-to-bar measurement</b> instead of silently trusting it.</li>
  <li>Typed-in candidate bikes are kept between launches.</li>
  <li>The Google Gemini coach now uses the latest <b>Flash</b> model — faster and more reliable, same cost.</li>
</ul>
]]></description>
